{"questionId":"16363","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Copper forms two chlorides, copper(I) chloride and copper(II) chloride.</span></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Two electrolysis cells were assembled using graphite electrodes and connected in series as shown.</span></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/0e2b920773da8385077e300e7d4c4df46d8aad7a.png\"></span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">Deduce the half-equation for the formation of the gas identified in (c)(iii).</span></p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">2H<sub>2</sub>O (l) → 4H<sup>+</sup> (aq) + O<sub>2</sub> (g) + 4e<sup>–</sup> ✔</span></p>\n<p><em><span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\">NOTE:&nbsp;Accept 2Cl<sup>–</sup> (aq) → Cl<sub>2</sub> (g) + 2e<sup>–</sup>.<br>Accept 4OH<sup>−</sup> → 2H<sub>2</sub>O + O<sub>2</sub> + 4e<sup>−</sup></span></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"16363","referenceCode":"19N.2.hl.TZ0.6c(iv)","subjectId":"45-dp-chemistry-last-assessment-2024","title":"Deduce the half-equation for the formation of the gas identified in (c)(iii).","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"c(iv)","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Core","Additional higher level (AHL)","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 19: Redox processes","19.1 Electrochemical cells","Additional higher level (AHL)","Topic 19: Redox processes","Core","Topic 1: Stoichiometric relationships","1.1 Introduction to the particulate nature of matter and chemical change","Core","Topic 1: Stoichiometric relationships"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}